{"cursor":"3476","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox officeholder |honorific-prefix = |name = Giovanni Battista Ceschi a\nSanta Croce |native_name = |native_name_lang = |honorific-suffix = |image = Jean-\nBaptiste Ceschi a Santa Croce.jpg |caption = |imagesize = |smallimage =  |alt = |caption = |order = |office\n= Lieutenant Grand Master (1871-1879) and Grand Master of the Order of Saint\nJohn (1879-1905) |term_start = 1871 |term_end = 24 January 1905 |monarch =\n|predecessor = Alessandro Borgia |successor = Galeas von Thun und Hohenstein\n|birth_date = 1827 |birth_place = Trento |death_date = 24 January 1905\n|death_place = Rome |restingplace = |restingplacecoordinates = |birthname =\n|citizenship = |nationality = Italian |party = |otherparty =  |spouse = |partner =  |relations = |children = |residence = |alma_mater =\n|occupation = |profession = |cabinet = |committees = |portfolio = |religion =\n|signature = |signature_alt = }}\n\nFra' 'Giovanni Battista Ceschi a Santa Croce' (Trento, 1827 â Rome, 24 January\n1905) was a leader of the Sovereign Military Order of Malta, succeeding\nAlessandro Borgia as its lieutenant in 1871, and then being chosen as the 74th\nPrince and Grand Master in 1879, a decision approved by pope Leo XIII on 28\nMarch that year. This made him the Order's first Grand Master after seventy\nyears of lieutenants and a peripatetic existence - this had begun to end with\nits becoming permanently based in Rome from 1834 onwards (from about 1889\nonwards it also had extraterritorial rights). During his tenure, Ceschi\ninitiated the creation of national lay associations of the order, made up of\nknights who would remain lay people and not take the Order's vows.\n","linknr":99,"url":"Giovanni_Battista_Ceschi_a_Santa_Croce","recorded":1375071599,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Giovanni_Battista_Ceschi_a_Santa_Croce&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Giovanni_Battista_Ceschi_a_Santa_Croce&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/